From David Wagner Subject Re The doctrine of Original Sin Alan E Alan Idler writes Alan We can also analyze to whom the Lord is addressing Marvel Alan not that I said unto thee Ye must be born again John Alan Here Jesus is clearly directing his remarks to Nicodemus a Alan ruler of the Jews not a child Yes but Jesus also made a very general and doctrinal statement in the same conversation Flesh gives birth to flesh but the Spirit gives birth to John Clearly infants are not born of the Thus without baptism they are They are not born with the image of God but in Adam's fallen image Gen They have no righteousness of their own just as adults have no righteousness of their There is only the imputed righteousness of Christ which believers receive through Alan We can ask ourselves why the Lord would even introduce the Alan concept of spiritual re birth through baptism if newborn babies Alan weren't free from sin Your point is a little obscure here but I think you are saying that Christ used the innocence of newborn babes as a metaphor for spiritual re But this is not what he If you look at the text he did not speak of spiritual re birth but of spiritual We are born of the Spirit once not twice or several We are also born of the flesh The Lord makes it clear that these are separate and different It is true that other Scriptures refer to spiritual birth as re birth because it is a second birth for example Titus But it is not a second spiritual The only thing the two births have in common is the concept of birth which is used as a symbol of new life' not of When an infant is born or conceived a new life is begun but it is neither innocent nor Similarly when that same individual is baptized or perhaps when they believe prior to baptism they begin a new life in Christ Romans Colossians Titus Ephesians Then the believer has God's assurance of the forgiveness of their sins and of Christ's imputed For references see The Augsburg Confession Article II Original Sin The Apology to the Augsburg Confession Article II Original Sin the Formula of Concord Article I Original Sin and Luther's Large Catechism Part For something more recent see Baptized into God's Family The Doctrine of Infant Baptism by Andrew Das available from Northwestern Publishing Andrew is a graduate of Concordia Lutheran Seminary Louis and is now pursuing doctoral studies at Yale Divinity David Wagner But mad reason rushes forth a confessional Lutheran and because Baptism is not dazzling like the works we do regards it as Martin Luther Large Catechism Part Baptism